Is Your Ideal Customer Profile Still Accurate?
Your entire lead generation strategy is built on one foundational assumption: that you know who your ideal customer is. But ICPs go stale faster than most teams realize. Company headcounts change. Decision-making hierarchies shift. Budget holders move between roles. Industries consolidate.

Ask yourself: When did you last conduct a thorough ICP audit? If the answer is more than 12 months ago, there is a real chance you are targeting the wrong companies, reaching out to the wrong contacts, or writing content that speaks to a buyer persona that no longer reflects reality.

A modern ICP audit in 2026 should draw from multiple data sources. Your CRM should inform you which closed-won accounts share the most attributes. Intent data should reveal which account types are actively researching your category. Conversation intelligence from sales calls should surface the language real buyers use and the problems they actually care about.

At Intent Amplify, our AI-powered demand generation platform helps clients continuously refine their ICP using real-time behavioral data and install base intelligence. This is not a one-time exercise. It is an ongoing process that keeps your targeting sharp as the market evolves.

Key audit questions to ask your team:

Have you updated your ICP in the last two quarters?
Does your ICP reflect firmographic, technographic, and psychographic attributes?
Are there recent wins or losses that challenge your existing assumptions?
Are You Generating Leads or Just Generating Noise?
Volume is not the same as value. This is one of the most important distinctions in modern B2B lead generation, and one of the most frequently blurred. Teams celebrate MQL numbers, campaign click-through rates, and form fills without asking whether any of it is translating into real pipeline movement.

According to research published in early 2026, more than 60 percent of B2B marketing-qualified leads never receive meaningful follow-up from sales. Not because sales teams are lazy, but because the leads are not actually qualified. They filled out a form for a content download. They attended a webinar. They clicked an ad. None of these actions necessarily signal purchase intent.

The more useful question is: What does genuine purchase intent look like for your solution? And are you measuring for that?

Intent signals, behavioral scoring, engagement depth, and account-level activity patterns are far stronger indicators of real interest than a one-time form fill. Your lead generation program in 2026 should be built around surfacing those signals, not just collecting contact information.

How Well-Aligned Are Your Sales and Marketing Teams?
Misalignment between sales and marketing remains one of the most expensive problems in B2B organizations. It shows up in predictable ways: marketing claims the leads are good, sales says they are not. Marketing points to MQL volume, sales points to low conversion rates. Both teams feel like they are doing their job. Neither team is fully wrong.

According to a 2026 industry analysis, companies with tightly aligned sales and marketing functions achieve 38 percent higher win rates and generate 208 percent more revenue from their marketing efforts than organizations operating in silos.

True alignment is not just about having a shared SLA document. It requires shared definitions, shared data access, shared feedback loops, and a culture where both teams see themselves as co-owners of revenue, not separate departments with separate scorecards.

Alignment checkpoints to review:

Do sales and marketing agree on the definition of a qualified lead?
How often do sales reps provide feedback on lead quality to marketing?
Are campaign results reviewed together in a shared meeting cadence?
Does marketing have visibility into what happens to leads after handoff?
