How Effectively Are You Targeting and Penetrating Key Accounts?
Account-based marketing has graduated from buzzword to boardroom priority for most mid-market and enterprise B2B organizations. In 2026, ABM is no longer a specialty play. It is how serious revenue teams operate when they have a defined universe of high-value accounts they want to win.

But the quality of ABM execution varies enormously. At one end of the spectrum, you have teams that have identified a target account list, are running coordinated multi-channel programs, are delivering personalized experiences at the account level, and are measuring success by account engagement and pipeline progression. At the other end, you have teams that have renamed their existing demand generation program as ABM without meaningfully changing anything about how they operate.

Where does your program sit on that spectrum?

Effective ABM in 2026 requires four things: a well-defined and regularly refreshed target account list, account-level intent and engagement data, the ability to deliver personalized content and experiences at scale, and tight coordination between marketing and sales on each target account. If any of those four elements is missing, your ABM program is likely underperforming its potential.

Are You Measuring the Metrics That Actually Matter?
Measurement is where many B2B lead generation programs quietly fail. Not because teams are not measuring anything, but because they are measuring the wrong things and drawing the wrong conclusions.

Vanity metrics like impressions, click-through rates, and raw MQL volume tell you about activity. They do not tell you about outcomes. Revenue-focused measurement looks different. It tracks metrics like pipeline coverage ratio, marketing-sourced revenue, cost per sales-qualified lead, account engagement rate, and lead-to-close velocity.

A 2026 benchmark from multiple B2B demand generation reports suggests that best-in-class organizations attribute revenue impact at every stage of the funnel, not just at the point of initial lead capture. They also regularly review attribution models to ensure that credit is being assigned in a way that reflects how buyers actually interact with their programs, not just which touchpoint happened to be last before a form fill.

Measurement questions to bring to your next revenue review:

What percentage of your closed revenue is directly attributable to marketing-generated pipeline?
What is your average lead-to-close velocity, and how has it changed over the past four quarters?
Are you tracking account-level engagement, or only individual contact-level activity?
Does your attribution model reflect the multi-touch reality of your buyers' journeys?
